## Design decisions worth noting

| Decision | Why |
|---|---|
| **Binary search** (`findFirstIndexAfter`) for window trimming | O(log n) vs O(n) `filter`. A single chatty IP with 10 000 stored timestamps cuts trimming from ~10 000 comparisons to ~14. The array stays sorted for free because `push(now)` is append-only and `Date.now()` is monotonically non-decreasing within a process. |
| **`cleanupInterval.unref()`** | Prevents the 60-second interval from keeping the Node event loop alive in tests or scripts that would otherwise exit cleanly. Standard Node.js pattern; guarded with `?.` for non-Node runtimes. |
| **`close()` on the returned object** | Separates the timer lifecycle from Express app teardown. Two limiters with different `windowMs` values need independent `close()` calls — a single global teardown hook handles it cleanly. |
| **`Retry-After` points at the oldest slot** | When the window is full, `timestamps[0]` is the oldest still-active request. It exits the window at `timestamps[0] + windowMs` — that's the earliest moment any new request could succeed. This gives clients a precise, non-pessimistic wait time. |
| **`X-RateLimit-Reset` after allowing** | After pushing the current timestamp, `timestamps[0]` is the oldest entry in the *new* window. Its expiry time is the next moment capacity increases — the most useful thing to tell well-behaved clients. |

